lanet], an online interactive search engine hosted by the United Nations Environment Programme's World Conservation Monitoring Center ([[UNEP-WCMC]]).\n*[http://www.protectplanetocean.org Protect Planet Ocean] \u2013 Marine Protected Areas site\n*[http://www.biodiversitya-z.org/areas/46/ A-Z of Areas of Biodiversity Importance: Marine Protected Areas]\n*[https://mpanews.openchannels.org MPA News: monthly news and analysis on marine protected areas worldwide]\n*[http://www.stanford.edu/group/microdocs/ Microdocs] \u2013 'The Short Attention Span Science Theater on Ecological Sustainability'\n*[http://www.cetaceanhabitat.org/ CetaceanHabitat.org] \u2013 Cetacean habitat directory for MPAs, national and international sanctuaries\n*[https://archive.is/20130416032701/http://www.whyfiles.org/295marine_reserve/ WhyFiles.org] \u2013 Huge Pacific reserve formed in Hawaii\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110928041444/http://www.wwf.org.uk/filelibrary/pdf/ma_overviewukmpa.pdf WWF: An Overview of Marine Protected Areas in the UK]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20130215150109/http://mpa.gov/pdf/helpful-resources/factsheets/mpamisconceptions2.pdf Misconceptions concerning MPAs (NOAA)]\n*[http://www.nature.com/news/2011/110812/full/news.2011.479.html New Research shows massive increase in biomass and diversity in what has been called the best MPA in the world]\n*[http://www.MPAtlas.org MPAtlas], a joint project of [[Marine Conservation Institute]] and the [[Waitt Foundation]]\n*[http://demonstrations.wolfram.com/CellularAutomataModelOfAnMPAFishery/ Cellular Automata Model of an MPA Fishery] ''Wolfram Demonstrations Project'' \u2014 requires [http://demonstrations.wolfram.com/download-cdf-player.html CDF player (free)]\n\n{{Marine protected areas}}\n{{fishery science topics}}\n{{Marine ecosystem topics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Marine Protected Area}}\n[[Category:Marine reserves| ]]\n[[Category:Marine conservation]]\n[[Category:Protected areas]]\n[[Category:Oceanography]]\n[[Category:Fisheries science]]\n[[Category:Fisheries law]]\n[[Category:Marine protected areas| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Protected areas of seas, oceans, estuaries or large lakes}}\n{{see also|Marine reserve|marine park}}\n{{About|marine protected areas specifically|protected regions of environmental or cultural value in general|protected area}}\n[[File:Milford sound 2004.jpg|thumb|250px|[[Milford Sound]], New Zealand is a ''strict [[marine reserve]]'' (Category Ia) [[Mitre Peak, New Zealand|Mitre Peak]], the mountain at left, rises {{convert|1692|m|abbr=on}} above the sea.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.protectedplanet.net/sites/Piopiotahi_Milford_Sound_Marine_Reserve/ |title=Milford Sound Marine Reserve |publisher=Protectedplanet.net |accessdate=2012-06-07}}</ref>]]\n'''Marine protected areas''' (MPA) are [[protected area]]s of [[sea]]s, [[ocean]]s, [[estuary|estuaries]] or in the US, the [[Great Lakes]] .<ref name=\"NOS\" >{{cite web|url=https://oceanservice.noaa.gov/facts/mpa.html |title=What is a marine protected area? |website=oceanservice.noaa.gov |accessdate=4 June 2019 |quote=In the U.S., MPAs span a range of habitats, including the open ocean, coastal areas, inter-tidal zones, estuaries, and the Great Lakes. }}</ref><!--marine is not normally used to refer to fresh water - this usage may be unique to NOAA--> These marine areas can come in many forms ranging from wildlife refuges to research facilities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://oceanservice.noaa.gov/facts/mpa.html|title=What is a marine protect?|last=Administration|first=US Department of Commerce, National Oceanic and Atmospheric|website=oceanservice.noaa.gov|language=EN-US|access-date=2018-02-05}}</ref> MPAs restrict human activity for a conservation purpose, typically to protect natural or cultural resources.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://oceanservice.noaa.gov/ecosystems/mpa/ |title=Marine Protected Areas |website=[[National Ocean Service]] |publisher=[[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]] |accessdate=2016-09-02}}</ref> Such marine resources are protected by local, state, territorial, native, regional, national, or international authorities and differ substantially among and between nations. This variation includes different limitations on development, fishing practices, fishing seasons and catch limits, moorings and bans on removing or disrupting [[marine life]]. In some situations (such as with the [[Phoenix Islands Protected Area]]), MPAs also provide revenue for countries, potentially equal to the income that they would have if they were to grant companies permissions to fish.<ref>National Geographic Magazine, January 2011</ref>\n\nOn 28 October 2016 in [[Hobart]], [[Australia]], the [[Convention for the Conservation of Antarctic Marine Living Resources]] agreed to establish the first [[Antarctica|Antarctic]] and largest marine protected area in the world encompassing 1.55 million km<sup>2</sup> (600,000 sq mi) in the [[Ross Sea]].<ref>{{cite news|title=CCAMLR to create world's largest Marine Protected Area|url=https://www.ccamlr.org/en/news/2016/ccamlr-create-worlds-largest-marine-protected-area|accessdate=28 October 2016|agency=Convention for the Conservation of Antarctic Marine Living Resources|date=28 October 2016}}</ref> Other large MPAs are in the [[Indian Ocean|Indian]], [[Pacific Ocean|Pacific]], and [[Atlantic Ocean]]s, in certain [[exclusive economic zone]]s of Australia and overseas territories of [[French overseas departments and territories|France]], the [[British Overseas Territories|United Kingdom]] and the [[Territories of the United States|United States]], with major ({{convert|990,000|km2|sqmi}} or larger) new or expanded MPAs by these nations since 2012&mdash;such as [[Natural Park of the Coral Sea]], [[Pacific Remote Islands Marine National Monument]], Coral Sea Commonwealth Marine Reserve and [[South Georgia and the South Sandwich Islands|South Georgia and the South Sandwich Islands Marine Protected Area]].<!--- for lead, limit to one large post 2011 example from each named country --->  When counted with MPAs of all sizes from many other countries, as of August 2016 there are more than 13,650 MPAs, encompassing 2.07% of the world's oceans, with half of that area &ndash; encompassing 1.03% of the world's oceans &ndash; receiving complete \"[[Marine protected area#Classifications|no-take\"]] designation.<ref name=\"MPAtlas\">{{cite web |url=http://www.mpatlas.org/explore/ |title=Explore |work=MPAtlas |publisher=[[Marine Conservation Institute]] |accessdate=2016-09-02}}</ref>\n\n==Terminology==\nThe [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]] (IUCN) defines a [[protected area]] as: \n<blockquote>\"A clearly defined geographical space, recognised, dedicated and managed, through legal or other effective means, to achieve the long-term conservation of nature with associated [[ecosystem services]] and cultural values.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iucn.org/about/union/commissions/wcpa/wcpa_puball/wcpa_pubsubject/wcpa_marinepub/?2135/Towards-Networks-of-Marine-Protected-Areas-The-MPA-Plan-of-Action-for-IUCNs-World-Commission-on-Protected-Areas |title=Towards Networks of Marine Protected Areas - The MPA Plan of Action for IUCN's World Commission on Protected Areas |publisher=IUCN |date=2008-11-04 |accessdate=2012-06-07 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121008225529/http://cmsdata.iucn.org/downloads/mpa_planofaction.pdf |archivedate=2012-05-22 }}</ref><ref name=\"IUCN 2012\" /></blockquote>\nThis definition is intended to make it more difficult to claim MPA status for regions where exploitation of marine resources occurs. If there is no defined long-term goal for conservation and ecological recovery and extraction of marine resources occurs, a region is not a marine protected area.<ref name=\"IUCN 2012\" >{{cite web|url=https://www.iucn.org/content/when-marine-protected-area-really-marine-protected-area |title=When is a Marine Protected Area really a Marine Protected Area |date=8 September 2012 |publisher=International Union for Conservation of Nature |accessdate=29 May 2019 }}</ref>\n\n\"Marine protected area (MPA)\" is a term for protected areas that include [[marine environment]] and [[biodiversity]].\n\nOther definitions by the IUCN include (2010):\n<blockquote>\"Any area of the intertidal or subtidal terrain, together with its overlying water and associated flora, fauna, historical and cultural features, which has been reserved by law or other effective means to protect part or all of the enclosed environment.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iucn.org/about/work/programmes/pa/pa_what/?4646/Marine-Protected-Areas--Why-have-them/ |title=Marine protected areas, why have them? |publisher=IUCN |date=2010-02-01 |accessdate=2012-06-07 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120319150803/http://www.iucn.org/about/work/programmes/pa/pa_what/?4646%2FMarine-Protected-Areas--Why-have-them%2F |archivedate=2012-03-19 }}</ref></blockquote>\n\nUnited States Executive Order 13158 in May 2000 established MPAs, defining them as;\n<blockquote>\"Any area of the marine environment that has been reserved by federal, state, tribal, territorial, or local laws or regulations to provide lasting protection for part or all of the natural and cultural resources therein.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.federalregister.gov/articles/2011/02/03/2011-2327/nomination-of-existing-marine-protected-areas-to-the-national-system-of-marine-protected-areas-and/ |title=Nomination of Existing Marine Protected Areas to the National System of Marine Protected Areas and Updates to the List of National System Marine Protected Areas |publisher=Federalregister.gov |accessdate=2012-06-07}}</ref></blockquote>\nThe [[Convention on Biological Diversity]] defined the broader term of ''marine and coastal protected area'' (MCPA);\n<blockquote>\"Any defined area within or adjacent to the marine environment, together with its overlying water and associated flora, fauna, historical and cultural features, which has been reserved by legislation or other effective means, including custom, with the effect that its marine and/or coastal biodiversity enjoys a higher level of protection than its surroundings.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=Marine Protected Areas (MPA) |url=http://www.biodiversitya-z.org/areas/46/ |title=Areas of Biodiversity Importance: Marine Protected Areas, 2010 |publisher=Biodiversitya-z.org |date=2010-10-15 |accessdate=2012-06-07}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nAn apparently unique extension of the meaning is used by [[NOAA]] to refer to protected areas on the Great Lakes of North America.<ref name=\"NOS\" />\n\n== Classifications ==\n[[File:Salomons Atoll in the Chagos.jpg|thumb|The [[Chagos Archipelago]] was declared the world's largest marine reserve in April 2010 with an area of 250,000 square miles until March 2015 when It was declared illegal by the Permanent Court of Arbitration.<ref>[http://www.fco.gov.uk/en/news/latest-news/?view=News&id=22001512/ Foreign and Commonwealth Office, New Protection for Marine Life, April, 2010]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110702165420/http://www.fco.gov.uk/en/news/latest-news/?view=News&id=22001512%2F |date=July 2, 2011 }}</ref>]]\n\nSeveral types of compliant MPA can be distinguished:\n*A totally marine area with no significant terrestrial parts.\n*An area containing both marine and terrestrial components, which can vary between two extremes; those that are predominantly maritime with little land (for example, an [[atoll]] would have a tiny island with a significant maritime population surrounding it), or that is mostly terrestrial.\n*Marine ecosystems that contain land and [[intertidal]] components only. For example, a [[mangrove forest]] would contain no open sea or ocean marine environment, but its river-like marine ecosystem nevertheless complies with the definition.\n\nIUCN offered seven [[IUCN Protected Area Management Categories|categories of protected area]], based on management objectives and four broad governance types.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Cat\n! [[IUCN]] [[Protected Area Management Categories]]:\n|-\n| <center>'''Ia'''</center>\n| '''Strict nature reserve'''<br>A [[marine reserve]] usually connotes \"maximum protection\", where all resource removals are strictly prohibited. In countries such as [[Kenya]] and [[Belize]], marine reserves allow for low-risk removals to sustain local communities.\n|-\n| <center>'''Ib'''</center>\n| '''Wilderness area'''\n|-\n| <center>'''II'''</center>\n| '''[[National park]]'''<br>[[Marine park]]s emphasize the protection of ecosystems but allow light human use. A marine park may prohibit fishing or extraction of resources, but allow recreation. Some marine parks, such as those in [[Tanzania]], are zoned and allow activities such as fishing only in low risk areas.\n|-\n| <center>'''III'''</center>\n| '''Natural monuments or features'''<br>Established to protect historical sites such as shipwrecks and cultural sites such as aboriginal fishing grounds.\n|-\n| <center>'''IV'''</center>\n| '''Habitat/species management area'''<br>Established to protect a certain species, to benefit [[fishery|fisheries]], rare [[Habitat (ecology)|habitat]], as spawning/nursing grounds for [[fish]], or to protect entire ecosystems.\n|-\n| <center>'''V'''</center>\n| '''Protected seascape'''<br>Limited active management, as with protected landscapes.\n|-\n| <center>'''VI'''</center>\n| '''Sustainable use of natural resources'''\n|}\n\nRelated [[protected area]] categories include the following;\n\n*[[World Heritage Site]] (WHS)&nbsp;\u2013 an area exhibiting extensive natural or cultural history. Maritime areas are poorly represented, however, with only 46 out of over 800 sites.\n*[[Man and the Biosphere]] \u2013 [[UNESCO]] program that promotes \"a balanced relationship between humans and the [[biosphere]]\". Under article 4, biosphere reserves must \"encompass a mosaic of ecological systems\", and thus combine terrestrial, coastal, or marine ecosystems. In structure they are similar to Multiple-use MPAs, with a core area ringed by different degrees of protection.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unesco.org/new/en/natural-sciences/environment/ecological-sciences/man-and-biosphere-programme/ |title=Man and the Biosphere Programme |publisher=UNESCO |accessdate=2012-06-07}}</ref>\n* [[Ramsar Convention|Ramsar site]] \u2013 must meet [[Ramsar Classification System for Wetland Type|certain criteria for the definition of \"Wetland\"]] to become part of a global system. These sites do not necessarily receive protection, but are indexed by importance for later recommendation to an agency that could designate it a protected area.<ref>[http://www.ramsar.org/pdf/ris/key_ris_e.pdf/ Information Sheet on Ramsar Wetlands] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110813143558/http://www.ramsar.org/pdf/ris/key_ris_e.pdf/ |date=August 13, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nWhile \"area\" refers to a single contiguous location, terms such as '''\"'''''network'''''\"''', '''\"'''''system'''''\"''', and '''\"'''''region'''''\"''' that group MPAs are not always consistently employed.'''\"'''''System'''''\"''' is more often used to refer to an individual MPA, whereas '''\"'''''region'''''\"''' is defined by the [[World Conservation Monitoring Centre]] as:\n<blockquote>\"A collection of individual MPAs operating cooperatively, at various spatial scales and with a range of protection levels that are designed to meet objectives that a single reserve cannot achieve.\"<ref>[http://www.wdpa-marine.org/MPAResources/MPAPlanningResources/Docs/Establishing%20resilient%20MPA%20networks-making%20it%20happen.pdf/ WDPA: Establishing Resilient Marine Protected Area Networks \u2014 Making It Happen, 2008] {{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nAt the 2004 [[Convention on Biological Diversity]], the agency agreed to use '''\"'''''network'''''\"''' on a global level, while adopting ''system'' for national and regional levels. The ''network'' is a mechanism to establish regional and local systems, but carries no authority or mandate, leaving all activity within the '''\"'''''system'''''\"'''.<ref>[http://www.unepscs.org/Refugia_Training/Fisheries%20Refugia%20Concept/15-Differences-Similarities-of-Fisheries-Refugia-and-Marine-Protected-Areas.pdf/ UNEP: Marine Protected Areas and the Concept of Fisheries Refugia, 2006/]{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n''No take zones'' (NTZs), are areas designated in a number of the world's MPAs, where all forms of exploitation are prohibited and severely limits human activities. These no take zones can cover an entire MPA, or specific portions. For example, the {{convert|1,150,000|km2|sqmi}} [[Papah\u0101naumoku\u0101kea Marine National Monument]], the world's largest MPA (and largest protected area of any type, land or sea), is a 100% no take zone.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mpatlas.org/mpa/sites/68808186/ |title=Papah\u0101naumoku\u0101kea (Expansion) Marine National Monument, United States |work=MPAtlas |publisher=[[Marine Conservation Institute]] |accessdate=2016-09-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160923124955/http://www.mpatlas.org/mpa/sites/68808186/ |archivedate=2016-09-23 }}</ref>\n\nRelated terms include; ''specially protected area'' (SPA), ''[[Special Area of Conservation]]'' (SAC), the United Kingdom's ''marine conservation zones'' (MCZs),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.naturalengland.org.uk/ourwork/marine/protectandmanage/mpa/conservationzones.aspx/ |title=Marine Conservation Zones |publisher=Naturalengland.org.uk |accessdate=2012-06-07}}</ref> or ''area of special conservation'' (ASC) etc. which each provide specific restrictions.\n\n== Stressors ==\nStressors that affect oceans include \"the impact of [[extractive industries]], localised pollution, and changes to its chemistry ([[ocean acidification]]) resulting from elevated [[carbon dioxide]] levels, due to our [[greenhouse gas|emissions]]\". MPAs have been cited as the ocean's single greatest hope for increasing the resilience of the marine environment to such stressors.<ref>Laffoley, D. d'A., (ed.) 2008. Towards Networks of Marine Protected Areas. The MPA Plan of Action for IUCN's World Commission on Protected Areas. IUCN WCPA, Gland, Switzerland. 28 pp.</ref> Well-designed and managed MPAs developed with input and support from interested stakeholders can conserve biodiversity and protect and restore [[fisheries]].\n\n== Economics ==\nMPAs can help sustain local economies by supporting fisheries and tourism.  For example, [[Apo Island]] in the [[Philippines]] made protected one quarter of their reef, allowing fish to recover, jumpstarting their economy. This was shown in the film, ''Resources at Risk: Philippine Coral Reef''.<ref name=\"autogenerated2007\">Christie, P. and A.T. White. 2007. Best practices for improved governance of coral reef marine protected areas. Coral Reefs 26:1047-1056.</ref> A 2016 report by the [[Center for Development and Strategy]] found that programs like the [[United States National Marine Sanctuary]] system can develop considerable economic benefits for communities through [[Public\u2013private partnership]]s.<ref name=\"Joint-Value Creation Between Marine Protected Areas and the Private Sector\">{{cite web|last1=Harary|first1=David|title=Joint-Value Creation Between Marine Protected Areas and the Private Sector|url=http://www.thinkcds.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/Final_MPA_Harary.pdf|website=thinkcds.org|publisher=Center for Development and Strategy|accessdate=26 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Management==\n\nTypical MPAs restrict [[fishing]], [[Petrochemicals|oil]] and [[natural gas|gas]] mining and/or [[tourism]]. Other restrictions may limit the use of [[ultrasonics|ultrasonic]] devices like [[sonar]] (which may confuse the guidance system of [[cetaceans]]), development, construction and the like. Some fishing restrictions include \"no-take\" zones, which means that no fishing is allowed. Less than 1% of US MPAs are no-take.\n\nShip transit can also be restricted or banned, either as a preventive measure or to avoid direct disturbance to individual species. The degree to which environmental regulations affect shipping varies according to whether MPAs are located in [[territorial waters]], [[exclusive economic zone]]s, or the [[high seas]]. The [[United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea|law of the sea]] regulates these limits.\n\nMost MPAs have been located in territorial waters, where the appropriate government can enforce them. However, MPAs have been established in exclusive economic zones and in [[international waters]]. For example, Italy, France and Monaco in 1999 jointly established a cetacean sanctuary in the [[Ligurian Sea]] named the [[Pelagos Sanctuary for Mediterranean Marine Mammals]]. This sanctuary includes both national and international waters. Both the [[Convention on Biological Diversity|CBD]] and [[IUCN]] recommended a variety of management systems for use in a protected area system. They advocated that MPAs be seen as one of many \"nodes\" in a network of protected areas.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.unep-wcmc.org/marine-protected-areas_470.html/ |archive-url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20111220214403/http://www.unep-wcmc.org/marine-protected-areas_470.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2011-12-20 |title=Marine Protected Area Networks |publisher=Unep-Wcmc |date=2011-01-18 |accessdate=2012-06-07 }}</ref> The following are the most common management systems:\n\n[[File:Asinara-Island01.jpg|thumb|right|Asinara, Italy is listed by WDPA as both a marine reserve and a national marine park, and as such could be labelled 'multiple-use'<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.protectedplanet.net/sites/Area_Naturale_Marina_Protetta_Isola_Dell_Asinara_Natural_Marine_Reserve_And_Natural_Protected_Marine_Areas/ |title=Asinara Natural Marine Reserve |publisher=Protectedplanet.net |accessdate=2012-06-07 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120608184308/http://www.protectedplanet.net/sites/Area_Naturale_Marina_Protetta_Isola_Dell_Asinara_Natural_Marine_Reserve_And_Natural_Protected_Marine_Areas |archivedate=2012-06-08 }}</ref>]]\n\n'''Seasonal and temporary management'''\u2014Activities, most critically fishing, are restricted seasonally or temporarily, e.g., to protect spawning/nursing grounds or to let a rapidly reducing species recover.\n\n'''Multiple-use MPAs'''\u2014These are the most common and arguably the most effective. These areas employ two or more protections. The most important sections get the highest protection, such as a no take zone and are surrounded with areas of lesser protections.\n\n'''Community involvement and related approaches'''\u2014Community-managed MPAs empower local communities to operate partially or completely independent of the governmental jurisdictions they occupy. Empowering communities to manage resources can lower conflict levels and enlist the support of diverse groups that rely on the resource such as subsistence and commercial fishers, scientists, recreation, tourism businesses, youths and others.\n\n===Marine Protected Area Networks===\n{{main|Marine Protected Area Network}}\n'''Marine Protected Area Networks''' or '''MPA networks''' have been defined as \"A group of MPAs that interact with one another ecologically and/or socially form a network\".<ref name=\"Christie, P. 2007\">Christie, P., and A. T. White. \"Best Practices for Improved Governance of Coral Reef Marine Protected Areas.\" Coral Reefs 26.4 (2007): 1047-056. Print.</ref>\n\nThese networks are intended to connect individuals and MPAs and promote education and cooperation among various administrations and user groups. \"MPA networks are, from the perspective of resource users, intended to address both environmental and socio-economic needs, complementary ecological and social goals and designs need greater research and policy support\".<ref name=\"Christie, P. 2007\" />\n\nFilipino communities connect with one another to share information about MPAs, creating a larger network through the social communities' support.<ref>Lowry, G. K., A. T. White, and P. Christie. \"Scaling Up to Networks of Marine Protected Areas in the Philippines: Biophysical, Legal, Institutional, and Social Considerations.\" Coastal Management 37.3 (2009): 274-90. Print.</ref> Emerging or established MPA networks can be found in [[Commonwealth marine reserves#Commonwealth marine reserve networks|Australia]], Belize, the [[Red Sea]], [[Gulf of Aden]] and Mexico.<ref name=\"Christie, P. 2007\" />\n\n==International efforts==\n\nThe 17th [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]] (IUCN) General Assembly in [[San Jose, California|San Jose]], California, the 19th IUCN assembly and the fourth World Parks Congress all proposed to centralise the establishment of protected areas. The [[Earth Summit 2002|World Summit on Sustainable Development]] in 2002 called for {{quote|the establishment of marine protected areas consistent with international laws and based on scientific information, including representative networks by 2012.<ref name=\"Wells13\">{{harvnb|Wells|Sheppard|van Lavieren|Barnard|2008|p=13|2008}}</ref>}} The Evian agreement, signed by [[G8|G8 Nations]] in 2003, agreed to these terms. The Durban Action Plan, developed in 2003, called for regional action and targets to establish a network of protected areas by 2010 within the jurisdiction of regional [[Environmental science|environmental protocols]].It recommended establishing protected areas for 20 to 30% of the world's oceans by the goal date of 2012. The [[Convention on Biological Diversity]] considered these recommendations and recommended requiring countries to set up marine parks controlled by a central organization before merging them. The [[United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change]] agreed to the terms laid out by the convention, and in 2004, its member nations committed to the following targets;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/nationalregional08well|title=National and Regional Networks of Marine Protected Areas: A Review of Progress|first=S.|last=Wells|date=23 May 2018|publisher=UNEP-WCMC / UNEP|via=Internet Archive}}</ref>\n\n*By 2006 complete an area system gap analysis at national and regional levels.\n*By 2008 address the less represented marine ecosystems, accounting for those beyond national jurisdiction in accordance.\n*By 2009 designate the protected areas identified through the gap analysis.\n*By 2012 complete the establishment of a comprehensive and ecologically representative network.\n[[File:Bunaken Marine Park.JPG|thumb|right|Bunaken Marine Park, Indonesia is officially listed as both a marine reserve and a national marine park.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.protectedplanet.net/search?q=Bunaken/ |title=Bunaken Marine Park |publisher=Protectedplanet.net |accessdate=2012-06-07}}</ref>]]\n\n<blockquote>\"The establishment by 2010 of terrestrial and by 2012 for marine areas of '''comprehensive, effectively managed, and ecologically representative national and regional systems of protected areas''' that collectively, inter alia through a global network, contribute to achieving the three objectives of the Convention and the 2010 target to significantly reduce the current late of [[biodiversity loss]] at the global, regional, national, and sub-national levels and contribute to poverty reduction and the pursuit of sustainable development.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbd.int/decision/cop/?id=7765/ |title=United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change, Decision VII/28 |publisher=Cbd.int |accessdate=2012-06-07}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nThe UN later endorsed another decision, Decision VII/15, in 2006:\n{{quote|Effective conservation of 10% of each of the world's ecological regions by 2010.<br><small> \u2013 [[United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change]] Decision VII/15</small><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbd.int/decision/cop/?id=7752/ |title=United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change, Decision VII/15 |publisher=Cbd.int |accessdate=2012-06-07}}</ref>}}\nThe 10% conservation goal is also found in [[Sustainable_Development_Goal|Sustainable Development Goal 14]] (which is part of the [[Convention on Biological Diversity]]) and which sets this 10% goal to a later date (2020). In 2017, the UN held the [[United Nations Ocean Conference]] aiming to find ways and urge for the implementation of Sustainable Development Goal 14. I that 2017 conference, it was clear that just between 3,6 and 5,7% of the world's oceans were protected, meaning another 6,4 to 4,3% of the world's oceans needed to be protected within 3 years. <ref>[https://news.nationalgeographic.com/2018/02/marine-protected-areas-assessment-environment-conservation-spd/ The World Has Two Years to Meet Marine Protection Goal. Can It Be Done?]</ref><ref>[https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0308597X17307686 Assessing real progress towards effective ocean protection]</ref>\nThe 10% protection goal is described as a \"baby step\" as 30% is the real amount of ocean protection scientists agree on that should be implemented.<ref>[https://news.nationalgeographic.com/2018/02/marine-protected-areas-assessment-environment-conservation-spd/ The World Has Two Years to Meet Marine Protection Goal. Can It Be Done?]</ref>\n\n===Global treaties===\n====United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea====\n\n====The Antarctic Treaty System====\nOn 7 April 1982, the Convention on the Conservation of Antarctic Marine Living Resources (CAMLR Convention) came into force after discussions began in 1975 between parties of the then-current [[Antarctic Treaty]] to limit large-scale exploitation of [[krill]] by commercial fisheries. The Convention bound contracting nations to abide by previously agreed upon Antarctic territorial claims and peaceful use of the region while protecting ecosystem integrity south of the [[Antarctic Convergence]] and [[60th parallel south|60 S latitude]]. In so doing, it also established a commission of the original signatories and acceding parties called the Commission for the Conservation of Antarctic Marine Living Resources (CCAMLR) to advance these aims through protection, scientific study, and rational use, such as harvesting, of those marine resources. Though separate, the Antarctic Treaty and CCAMLR, make up part the broader system of international agreements called the Antarctic Treaty System. Since 1982, the CCAMLR meets annually to implement binding conservations measures like the creation of 'protected areas' at the suggestion of the convention's scientific committee.\n\nIn 2009, the CCAMLR created the first 'high-seas' MPA entirely within international waters over the southern shelf of the [[South Orkney Islands]]. This area encompasses {{convert|94,000|km2|sqmi}} and all fishing activity including transhipment, and dumping or discharge of waste is prohibited with the exception of scientific research endeavors.<ref>{{cite web|title=Protection of the South Orkney Islands southern shelf|url=https://www.ccamlr.org/en/measure-91-03-2009|website=www.ccamlr.org|publisher=Commission for the Conservation of Antarctic Marine Living Resources|accessdate=29 October 2016}}</ref> On 28 October 2016, the CCAMLR, composed of 24 member countries and the European Union at the time, agreed to establish the world's largest marine park encompassing 1.55 million km<sup>2</sup> (600,000 sq mi) in the Ross Sea after several years of failed negotiations. Establishment of the Ross Sea MPA required unanimity of the commission members and enforcement will begin in December 2017. However, due to a sunset provision inserted into the proposal, the new marine park will only be in force for 35 years.<ref>{{cite news|title=CCAMLR to create world's largest Marine Protected Area|url=https://www.ccamlr.org/en/news/2016/ccamlr-create-worlds-largest-marine-protected-area|accessdate=29 October 2016|publisher=Commission for the Conservation of Antarctic Marine Living Resources|date=29 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Regional Organizations===\n====PIMPAC====\nPacific Islands Marine Protected Areas Community\n{{expand section|date=December 2017}}\n\n====NAMPAN====\nNorth American Marine Protected Areas Network\n{{expand section|date=December 2017}}\n\n====CCAMLR====\nConvention on the Conservation of Antarctic Marine Living Resources\n{{expand section|date=December 2017}}\n\n===National Targets===\n\nMany countries have established national targets, accompanied by action plans and implementations. The UN Council identified the need for countries to collaborate with each other to establish effective regional conservation plans. Some national targets are listed in the table below<ref name=\"Wells15\" >{{harvnb|Wells|Sheppard|van_Lavieren|Barnard|2008|p=15}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Country\n! Plan of action\n|-\n| [[American Samoa]]\n| 20% of reefs to be protected by 2010\n|-\n| [[Australia]] \u2013 [[South Australia]]\n| 19 marine protected areas by 2010\n|-\n| [[Bahamas]]\n| 20% of the marine ecosystem protected for fishery replenishment by 2010.<br/>20% of coastal and marine habitats by 2015.\n|-\n| [[Belize]]\n| 20% of [[bioregion]]s.\n\n30% of [[Coral reef]]s.\n\n60% of [[Turtle|turtle nesting sites]].\n\n30% of [[Manatee|Manatee distribution]].\n\n60% of [[American crocodile|American crocodile nesting]].\n\n80% of [[Breed|breeding areas]].\n|-\n| [[Canada]]\n| 10% marine conservation areas by 2020.<ref>{{cite web|title=Reaching marine conservation targets |website=[[Government of Canada]] |url=https://www.dfo-mpo.gc.ca/oceans/conservation/plan/index-eng.html |accessdate=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Chile]]\n| 10% of marine areas by 2010. National network for organization by 2015.\n|-\n| [[Cuba]]\n| 22% of land habitat, including:\n\n:15% of the insular shelf\n\n:25% of [[coral reef]]s\n\n:25% of [[wetland]]s\n|-\n| [[Dominican Republic]]\n| 20% of marine and coastal by 2020.\n|-\n| [[Micronesia]]\n| 30% of shoreline ecosystems by 2020.\n|-\n| [[Fiji]]\n| 30% of reefs by 2015.\n\n30% of water managed by marine protected areas by 2020.\n|-\n| [[Germany]]\n| 38% of water managed by the marine protected network. (no set date)\n|-\n| [[Grenada]]\n| 25% of nearby marine resources by 2020.\n|-\n| [[Guam]]\n| 30% of nearby marine ecosystem by 2020.\n|-\n| [[Indonesia]]\n| 100,000&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup> by 2010.\n\n200,000&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup> by 2020.\n|-\n| [[Republic of Ireland]]\n|14% of territorial waters as of 2009<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indexmundi.com/facts/ireland/marine-protected-areas/ |title=Irish marine protected areas |publisher=Indexmundi.com |accessdate=2012-06-07}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Isle of Man]]\n|10% of Manx waters as 'effectively managed, ecologically representative and well-connected protected areas and other effective area-based conservation measures' by 2020.  As of June 2016, approximately 3% of Manx waters were protected as a [[Marine Nature Reserve]], with additional areas subject to seasonal or temporary protection.<ref>https://www.gov.im/media/1346374/biodiversity-strategy-2015-final-version.pdf</ref>\n|-\n| [[Jamaica]]\n| 20% of marine habitats by 2020.\n|-\n| [[Madagascar]]\n| 100,000&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup> by 2012.\n|-\n| [[Marshal Islands]]\n| 30% of nearby marine ecosystem by 2020.\n|-\n| [[New Zealand]]\n| 20% of marine environment by 2010.\n|-\n| [[Northern Mariana Islands|North Mariana Islands]]\n| 30% of nearby marine ecosystem by 2020.\n|-\n| [[Palau]]\n| 30% of nearby marine ecosystem by 2020.\n|-\n| [[Peru]]\n| Marine protected area system established by 2015.\n|-\n| [[Philippines]]\n| 10% fully protected by 2020.\n|-\n| [[Senegal]]\n| Creation of MPA network. (no set date)\n|-\n| [[South Africa]]\n| 10% of exclusive economic zone by 2020\n|-\n| [[St. Vincent and the Grenadines]]\n| 20% of marine areas by 2020.\n|-\n| [[Tanzania]]\n| 10% of marine area by 2010; 20% by 2020.\n|-\n| [[United Kingdom]]\n| Establish an ecologically coherent network of marine protected areas by 2012.\n|-\n| [[United States]] \u2013 [[California]]\n| 29 MPAs covering 18% of state marine area with {{convert|243|km2}} at maximum protection.\n|}\n\nThe prevalent practice of area-based targets was criticized in 2019 by a group of environmental scientists because politicians tended to protect parts of the oceans where little fishing happened to meet the goals. The lack of fishing in these areas made them easy to protect, but it also had little positive impact.<ref>{{cite journal| last = Kuempel| first= Caitlin| last2= Jones| first2= Kendall| last3 = Watson| first3= James| last4= Possingham| first4= James| date = 27 May 2017| title = Quantifying biases in marine-protected-area placement relative to abatable threats| journal = Conservation Biology| volume= 33| issue= 6| pages= 1350\u20131359| doi        = 10.1111/cobi.13340| pmid= 31131932| pmc= 6899811}}</ref>\n\n==National efforts==\n\nThe marine protected area network is still in its infancy. As of October 2010, approximately 6,800 MPAs had been established, covering 1.17% of global ocean area. Protected areas covered 2.86% of exclusive economic zones (EEZs).<ref name=\"iucn.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.iucn.org/knowledge/publications_doc/publications/?6500/Global-ocean-protection--present-status-and-future-possibilities/ |title=Global Ocean Protection: Present Status and Future Possibilities |publisher=Iucn.org |date=2010-11-23 |accessdate=2012-06-07}}</ref> MPAs covered 6.3% of territorial seas.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mdgs.un.org/unsd/mdg/Host.aspx?Content=Products/ProgressReports.htm/ |title=UN (2010) Millennium Development Goals Report \u2013 Addendum |publisher=Mdgs.un.org |accessdate=2012-06-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170927112249/https://mdgs.un.org/unsd/mdg/Host.aspx?Content=Products%2FProgressReports.htm%2F |archive-date=2017-09-27 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Many prohibit the use of harmful fishing techniques yet only 0.01% of the ocean's area is designated as a \"no take zone\".<ref>Christie, Patrick, and A.T White. \"Best practices for improved governance of coral reef marine protected areas.\" (2007): 1048-1056. Print.</ref> This coverage is far below the projected goal of 20%-30%<ref>{{cite journal |last=Halpern |first=B. |year=2003 |title=The impact of marine reserves: do reserves work and does reserve size matter? |doi= 10.1890/1051-0761(2003)013[0117:TIOMRD]2.0.CO;2 |journal=Ecological Applications |volume=13 |pages=117\u2013137 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.wiomsa.org/mpatoolkit/Themesheets/I1_No_take_areas.pdf No Take Areas] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120324104255/http://www.wiomsa.org/mpatoolkit/Themesheets/I1_No_take_areas.pdf |date=March 24, 2012 }}</ref> Those targets have been questioned mainly due to the cost of managing protected areas and the conflict that protections have generated with human demand for marine goods and services.<ref name=\"MoraAndSale2011\">{{ cite journal | url=https://www.int-res.com/articles/theme/m434p251.pdf | last1=Mora |first1=C |last2=Sale |first2=P | year=2011 | title=Ongoing global biodiversity loss and the need to move beyond protected areas: A review of the technical and practical shortcoming of protected areas on land and sea | journal=Marine Ecology Progress Series | volume = 434 | pages = 251\u2013266 | doi=10.3354/meps09214}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |first1=Louisa J. |last1=Wooda |first2=Lucy |last2=Fisha |first3=Josh |last3=Laughrena |first4=Daniel |last4=Pauly |title= Assessing Progress Towards Global Marine Protection Targets: Shortfalls in Information and Action |year=2008 |journal=Oryx |volume=42 |issue=3 |pp=340\u2013351 |doi=10.1017/S003060530800046X |doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\n===Africa===\n\n====South Africa====\n{{main|Marine protected areas of South Africa}}\n\nA '''marine protected area of South Africa''' is an area of coastline or ocean within the [[exclusive economic zone]] (EEZ) of the Republic of [[South Africa]] that is protected in terms of specific legislation.<ref name=\"Protecting the ocean\">{{cite web|url=https://www.marineprotectedareas.org.za/protecting-the-ocean |title=Protecting the ocean |website=www.marineprotectedareas.org.za |accessdate=18 January 2019 }}</ref>\n\nThere are a total of 45 [[marine protected area]]s in the South African EEZ, with a total area of 5% of the waters. The target is to have 10% of the oceanic waters protected by 2020. All but one of the MPAs are in the coastal waters off continental South Africa, and one is off [[Prince Edward Island]] in the [[Southern Ocean]].\n\n===Greater Caribbean===\n\n[[File:Location Caribbean.png|thumb|300px|The [[Caribbean]] region; the UNEP\u2013defined region also includes the [[Gulf of Mexico]]. This region is encompassed by the [[Mesoamerican Barrier Reef System]] proposal, and the Caribbean challenge]]\n[[File:GulfofMexico3D.jpg|thumb|The [[Gulf of Mexico]] region (in 3D) is encompassed{{clarify|reason= how is the region \"encompassed\" by this proposal?|date=February 2019}} by the \"Islands in the Stream\" proposal.]]\nThe [[Caribbean|Greater Caribbean]] subdivision encompasses an area of about {{convert|5700000|km2}} of ocean and 38 nations. The area includes island countries like the [[Bahamas]] and [[Cuba]], and the majority of [[Central America]]. The Convention for Protection and Development of the Marine Environment of the Wider Caribbean Region (better known as the [[Curitiba#UN Convention on Biodiversity|Cartagena Convention]]) was established in 1983. [[Cartagena Protocol on Biosafety|Protocols involving protected areas]] were ratified in 1990. As of 2008, the region hosted about 500 MPAs. [[Coral reef]]s are the best represented.\n\nTwo networks are under development, the [[Mesoamerican Barrier Reef System]] (a long [[Coral reef|barrier reef]] that borders the coast of much of Central America), and the \"Islands in the Stream\" program (covering the [[Gulf of Mexico]]).<ref name=\"Wells33\">{{harvnb|Wells|Sheppard|van_Lavieren|Barnard|2008|p=33}}</ref>\n\n===Southeast Asia===\nSoutheast Asia is a global epicenter for marine diversity. 12% of its coral reefs are in MPAs. The Philippines have some the world's best coral reefs and protect them to attract international tourism. Most of the Philippines' MPAs are established to secure protection for its coral reef and [[sea grass]] habitats. Indonesia has MPAs designed for tourism and relies on tourism as a main source of income.<ref name=\"autogenerated2007\"/>\n\n==== Philippines ====\nThe [[Philippines]] host one of the most highly biodiverse regions, with 464 reef-building coral species. Due to overfishing, destructive fishing techniques, and rapid coastal development, these are in rapid decline. The country has established some 600 MPAs. However, the majority are poorly enforced and are highly ineffective. However, some have positively impacted reef health, increased fish biomass, decreased coral bleaching and increased yields in adjacent fisheries. One notable example is the MPA surrounding Apo Island.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reefbase.org/key_topics/pdf/Philippines%20mpa.pdf|title=Summary Report for MPAs in the Philippines|author=|date=|website=reefbase.org}}</ref>\n\n===Latin America===\n\n[[Latin America]] has designated one large MPA system. As of 2008, 0.5% of its marine environment was protected, mostly through the use of small, multiple-use MPAs.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{harvnb|Wells|Sheppard|van_Lavieren|Barnard|2008}}</ref>\n\n===South Pacific===\n\nThe South Pacific network ranges from [[Belize]] to [[Chile]]. Governments in the region adopted the [[List of international environmental agreements#Marine environment \u2013 global conventions|Lima convention]] and action plan in 1981. An MPA-specific protocol was ratified in 1989. The permanent commission on the exploitation and conservation on the marine resources of the South Pacific promotes the exchange of studies and information among participants.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\nThe region is currently running one comprehensive cross-national program, the Tropical Eastern Pacific Marine Corridor Network, signed in April 2004. The network covers about {{convert|211000000|km2}}.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\nOne alternative to imposing MPAs on an indigenous population is through the use of [[Indigenous Protected Areas]], such as those in Australia.\n\n===North Pacific===\n\nThe North Pacific network covers the western coasts of Mexico, Canada, and the U.S. The \"Antigua Convention\" and an action plan for the north Pacific region were adapted in 2002. Participant nations manage their own national systems.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> In 2010\u20132011, the State of California completed hearings and actions via the state Department of Fish and Game to establish new MPAs.{{Citation needed|date = December 2014}}\n\n===United States and Pacific Island Territories===\n{{see|United States National System of Marine Protected Areas|United States National Marine Sanctuary}}\n{{summarize section|date=February 2019}}\nPresident [[Barack Obama]] signed a proclamation on September 25, 2014, designating the world's largest marine reserve. The proclamation expanded the existing [[Pacific Remote Islands Marine National Monument]], one of the world's most pristine tropical marine environments, to six times its current size, encompassing {{Convert|490000|sqmi}} of protected area around these islands. Expanding the Monument protected the area's unique deep coral reefs and seamounts.<ref>[http://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2014/09/24/fact-sheet-president-obama-designate-largest-marine-monument-world-limit President Obama Designates Largest Marine Monument] 25 Sept 2014 Retrieved 25 Sept 2014</ref>\n\n[[File:Central California Marine Sanctuaries.jpg|thumb|Diagram illustrating the orientation of the 3 [[National Marine Sanctuary|marine sanctuaries]] of Central California: [[Cordell Bank]], [[Gulf of the Farallones]], and [[Monterey Bay National Marine Sanctuary|Monterey Bay]]. Davidson Seamount, part of the Monterey Bay sanctuary, is indicated at bottom-right.]]\nIn April 2009, the US established a [[United States National System of Marine Protected Areas]], which strengthens the protection of US ocean, coastal and [[Great Lakes]] resources. These large-scale MPAs should balance \"the interests of conservationists, fishers, and the public.\"<ref name=\"Christie, P. 2007\"/> As of 2009, 225 MPAs participated in the national system. Sites work together toward common national and regional conservation goals and priorities. NOAA's national marine protected areas center maintains a comprehensive inventory<ref>[http://mpa.gov/helpful_resources/inventory.html MPA Inventory] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100328215720/http://mpa.gov/helpful_resources/inventory.html |date=March 28, 2010 }}</ref> of all 1,600+ MPAs within the US exclusive economic zone. Most US MPAs.allow some type of extractive use. Fewer than 1% of U.S. waters prohibit all extractive activities.<ref name=\"mpa.gov\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mpa.gov/ |title=Marine Protected Areas Government Website |publisher=Mpa.gov |date=2012-05-07 |accessdate=2012-06-07 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120606073524/http://www.mpa.gov/ |archivedate=2012-06-06 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1981 [[Olympic National Park]] became a marine protected area. The total protected site area is {{Convert|3697|km2}}. 173.2&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup> of the area was an MPA.<ref name=\"mpaglobal.org\">{{cite web |author=www.cognitiveDesign.net |url=http://www.mpaglobal.org/index.php?action=showMain&site_code=2579 |title=Olympic National Park World Heritage Site - a Marine Protected Area in USA (contiguous states) - Overview |publisher=MPA Global |date=1981-01-01 |accessdate=2012-06-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120312074032/http://www.mpaglobal.org/index.php?action=showMain&site_code=2579 |archive-date=2012-03-12 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The national system is a mechanism to foster MPA collaboration.<ref name=\"thefederalregister.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thefederalregister.com/d.p/2010-01-07-E9-31406 |title=Notices: Nomination of Existing Marine Protected Areas to the National System of Marine \u00bb Federal Register [FR Doc E9-31406&#93; |publisher=Thefederalregister.com |accessdate=2012-06-07}}</ref> Sites that meet pertinent criteria are eligible to join the national system. Four entry criteria govern admission:\n* Meets the definition of an MPA as defined in the Framework.\n* Has a management plan (can be sitespecific or part of a broader programmatic management plan; must have goals and objectives and call for monitoring or evaluation of those goals and objectives).\n* Contributes to at least one priority conservation objective as listed in the Framework.\n* Cultural heritage MPAs must also conform to criteria for the National Register for Historic Places.\"<ref name=\"thefederalregister.com\" />\nIn 1999, California adopted the [[Marine Life Protection Act]], establishing the first state law requiring a comprehensive, science-based MPA network. The state created the [[Marine Life Protection Act|Marine Life Protection Act Initiative]]. The MLPA Blue Ribbon Task Force and stakeholder and scientific advisory groups ensure that the process uses the science and public participation.\n\nThe MLPA Initiative established a plan to create California's statewide MPA network by 2011 in several steps. The Central Coast step was successfully completed in September, 2007.  The North Central Coast step was completed in 2010.  The South Coast and North Coast steps were expected to go into effect in 2012.<ref>Department of Fish and Game. \"http://www.dfg.ca.gov/mlpa/</ref>\n\n===Indian Ocean===\nIn exchange for some of its [[Government debt|national debt]] being written off, the [[Seychelles]] designates two new [[marine protected area]]s in the [[Indian Ocean]], covering about {{convert|210000|km2|mi2|}}. It is the result of a financial deal, brokered in 2016 by [[The Nature Conservancy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-43154686|title=Seychelles starts 'Britain-sized' reserve|author=|date=22 February 2018|publisher=|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://phys.org/news/2018-02-seychelles-huge-marine-reserve.html|title=Seychelles designates huge new marine reserve|author=|date=|website=phys.org}}</ref>\n\n===United Kingdom and British Overseas Territories===\n\n====United Kingdom====\nThere are a number of marine protected areas around the [[coastline of the United Kingdom]], known as [[Marine Conservation Zone]]s in England, Wales, and Northern Ireland, and [[Marine Protected Areas in Scotland|Marine Protected Area]]s in Scotland.<ref>{{cite web|title=Marine Protected Areas around the UK|url=http://www.wildlifetrusts.org/MPA|publisher=The Wildlife Trusts|accessdate=19 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Protecting and sustainably using the marine environment|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/policies/protecting-and-sustainably-using-the-marine-environment/supporting-pages/marine-protected-areas|publisher=UK Government|accessdate=19 March 2015|date=30 January 2015}}</ref> They are to be found in inshore and offshore waters.<ref>{{cite web|title=Map|url=http://www.ukmpas.org/mapper.php|publisher=UK Marine Protected Areas Centre|accessdate=19 March 2015}}{{cite web|title=Marine Protected Areas in the UK|url=http://jncc.defra.gov.uk/page-5201|publisher=Joint Nature Conservation Committee|accessdate=19 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n====British Overseas Territories====\nThe United Kingdom is also creating marine protected reserves around several [[British Overseas Territories]].\nThe UK is responsible for 6.8 million square kilometres of ocean around the world, larger than all but four other countries.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2015/feb/10/conservationists-call-for-uk-to-create-worlds-largest-marine-reserve|title=Conservationists call for UK to create world's largest marine reserve|work=The Guardian|date=15 February 2015|accessdate=4 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Chagos Marine Protected Area]] in the Indian Ocean was established in 2010 as a \"no-take-zone\". With a total surface area of  {{convert|640,000|km2|sqmi}}, it was the world's largest contiguous marine reserve.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chagos Marine Reserve, British Indian Ocean Territory|url=http://www.marinereservescoalition.org/resources/marine-reserves-around-the-world/chagos-marine-reserve-british-indian-ocean-territory/|publisher=Marine Reserves Coalition|accessdate=19 March 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402090301/http://www.marinereservescoalition.org/resources/marine-reserves-around-the-world/chagos-marine-reserve-british-indian-ocean-territory/|archivedate=2 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Chagos Marine Reserve|url=http://chagos-trust.org/about/chagos-marine-reserve|publisher=Chagos Conservation Trust|accessdate=19 March 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120705221356/http://chagos-trust.org/about/chagos-marine-reserve|archivedate=5 July 2012}}</ref> In March 2015, the UK announced the creation of a marine reserve around the [[Pitcairn Islands]] in the Southern Pacific Ocean to protect its special biodiversity. The area of {{convert|830,000|km2|sqmi}} surpassed the Chagos Marine Protected Area as the world's largest contiguous marine reserve,<ref name=\"NatGeo20150318\">{{cite news|title=World's Largest Single Marine Reserve Created in Pacific|url=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/2015/03/150318-pitcairn-marine-reserve-protected-area-ocean-conservation/|accessdate=19 March 2015|work=National Geographic|publisher=World\u2019s Largest Single Marine Reserve Created in Pacific|date=18 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Pitcairn Islands get huge marine reserve|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/science-environment-31943633|accessdate=19 March 2015|publisher=BBC|date=18 March 2015}}{{cite news|title=Pitcairn Islands to get world's largest single marine reserve|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2015/mar/18/pitcairn-islands-marine-reserve-budget-2015|accessdate=19 March 2015|publisher=The Guardian|date=18 March 2015}}</ref> until the August 2016 expansion of the [[Papah\u0101naumoku\u0101kea Marine National Monument]] in the United States to {{convert|1,510,000|km2|sqmi}}.\n\nIn January 2016, the UK government announced the intention to create a marine protected area around [[Ascension Island]]. The protected area will be {{convert|234,291|km2|sqmi}}, half of which will be closed to fishing.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-35216313|title=Ascension Island to become marine reserve|date=3 January 2016|accessdate=3 January 2016|work=BBC}}</ref>\n\n===Europe===\n\nThe [[Natura 2000]] [[ecological network|ecological MPA network]] in the [[European Union]] included MPAs in the [[North Atlantic]], the [[Mediterranean Sea]] and the [[Baltic Sea]]. The member states had to define NATURA 2000 areas at sea in their [[Exclusive Economic Zone]].\n\nTwo assessments, conducted thirty years apart, of three Mediterranean MPAs, demonstrate that proper protection allows commercially valuable and slow-growing red coral ([[Corallium rubrum]]) to produce large colonies in shallow water of less than {{convert|50|m}}. Shallow-water colonies outside these decades-old MPAs are typically very small. The MPAs are [[Banyuls]], [[Carry-le-Rouet]] and Scandola, off the island of [[Corsica]].<ref name=sd>{{cite journal\n|journal=Science Daily\n|url=https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2010/05/100511102115.htm\n|title=Marine Protected Areas Conserve Mediterranean Red Coral\n|date=May 11, 2010|accessdate=June 11, 2010}}</ref>\n\n*[[Mediterranean Science Commission]]; proposed the creation of 7 marine protected areas (\"peace parcs\")<ref>{{cite web|url=http://magazine.nationalgeographic.nl/2011/02/22/in-het-kielzog-van-jacques-cousteau/ |title=7 peace parcs proposed by CIESM |publisher=Magazine.nationalgeographic.nl |accessdate=2012-06-07 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110228162959/http://magazine.nationalgeographic.nl/2011/02/22/in-het-kielzog-van-jacques-cousteau/ |archivedate=2011-02-28 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ciesm.org |title=CIESM webpage |publisher=Ciesm.org |accessdate=2012-06-07}}</ref>\n\n* WWF together with other partners<ref>[http://medpan.org/about/medpan/organisation/ The association]</ref> proposed the creation of MedPan (Network of Marine Protected Areas Managers in the Mediterranean) which aims to protect 10% of the surface of the mediterranean by 2020<ref>[http://mediterranean.panda.org/?206841 The Mediterranean needs more marine reserves \u2013 they are an antidote to the crisis, says WWF]</ref>\n\nA 2018 study published in [[Science (journal)|Science]] found that trawling is more intense inside official EU marine sanctuaries and that endangered fish species such as sharks and rays are more common outside them.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2018/dec/20/marine-life-worse-off-inside-protected-areas-analysis-reveals  Marine life worse off inside 'protected' areas, analysis reveals] The Guardian, 2019</ref>\n\n===Notable marine protected areas===\n{{clarify|Reason=What makes these specifically notable?|date=February 2019}}\n[[File:Marine protected areas detailed map.jpg|350px|thumb|right|Marine protected areas]]\n* The [[Bowie Seamount|Bowie Seamount Marine Protected Area]] off the [[British Columbia Coast|coast of British Columbia]], Canada.\n* The [[Great Barrier Reef Marine Park]] in [[Queensland, Australia|Queensland]], Australia.\n* The [[Ligurian Sea Cetacean Sanctuary]] in the seas of Italy, [[Monaco]] and France.\n* The [[Dry Tortugas National Park]] in the [[Florida Keys]], USA.\n* The [[Papah\u0101naumoku\u0101kea Marine National Monument]] in [[Hawaii]].\n* The [[Phoenix Islands Protected Area]], [[Kiribati]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.conservation.org/newsroom/pressreleases/Pages/PIPA-largest-protected-area-in-pacific.aspx |title=Conservation International \u2013 World's Largest Marine Protected Area Created in Pacific Ocean |publisher=Conservation.org |accessdate=2012-06-07}}</ref>\n* The [[Channel Islands National Marine Sanctuary]] in [[California]], USA.{{sfn|Smith|Miller|2003|}}\n* The [[Chagos Marine Protected Area]] in the [[Indian Ocean]].<ref>{{cite web|last=North Sea Marine Cluster |title=Managing Marine Protected Areas |url=http://nsmc.eu.com/Marine-Protected-Areas-Report-3.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130530213720/http://nsmc.eu.com/Marine-Protected-Areas-Report-3.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=30 May 2013 |publisher=NSMC |accessdate=11 February 2013 }}</ref>\n*The [[Wadden Sea]] bordering the [[North Sea]] in the Netherlands, Germany, and Denmark.\n\n===Marine protected areas as percentage of territorial waters===\n<!-- Color scheme= \n0 \u2013 2,5% = red\n2,5 \u2013 5% = orange\n5 \u2013 7,5% = yellow\n7,5- 10% = green\n10%+ = blue\nno data or landlocked country = grey\n-->\nThe following shows a list of countries and their marine protected areas as percentage of their territorial waters (click \"show\" to expand).<ref>{{cite web| url=https://data.worldbank.org/indicator/ER.MRN.PTMR.ZS| title=Marine protected areas % of territorial waters| date=2016-2017| publisher=The World Bank| accessdate=March 12, 2019}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable collapsible collapsed\" style=\"text-align: center; font-size: 85%; width: auto; table-layout: fixed;\"\n|-\n! Country\n! MPA in % of territorial waters in 2017\n|-\n| Albania\n| {{ font color | orange | 2.72 }}\n|-\n| Algeria\n| {{ font color | red | 0.09 }}\n|