{ font color | orange | 2.99}}\n|-\n| Turks and Caicos Islands\n| {{ font color | red | 0.10 }}\n|-\n| Tuvalu\n| {{ font color | red | 0.01 }}\n|-\n| Ukraine\n| {{ font color | orange | 3.42 }}\n|-\n| United Arab Emirates\n| {{ font color | blue | 11.27 }}\n|-\n| United Kingdom\n| {{ font color | blue | 28.87 }}\n|-\n| United States\n| {{ font color | blue | 41.06 }}\n|-\n| Uruguay\n| {{ font color | red | 0.72 }}\n|-\n| Vanuatu\n| {{ font color | red | 0.01 }}\n|-\n| Venezuela, RB\n| {{ font color | orange | 3.49 }}\n|-\n| Vietnam\n| {{ font color | red | 0.56 }}\n|-\n| Virgin Islands (U.S.)\n| {{ font color | red | 0.85 }}\n|-\n| Yemen, Rep.\n| {{ font color | red | 0.47 }}\n|-\n|}\n\n==Assessment==\n[[File:Anguilla Prickly-Pear.jpg|thumb|The [[Prickly Pear Cays]] are a marine protected area, roughly six miles from Road Bay, [[Anguilla]], in the [[Leeward Islands]] of the Caribbean.]]\nManagers and scientists use [[geographic information system]]s and [[remote sensing]] to map and analyze MPAs. NOAA Coastal Services Center compiled an \"Inventory of GIS-Based Decision-Support Tools for MPAs.\" The report focuses on GIS tools with the highest utility for MPA processes.<ref name=\"mpa.gov\"/> Remote sensing uses advances in [[aerial photography]] [[image capture]], [[pop-up archival satellite tag]]s, [[satellite imagery]], acoustic data, and [[radar imagery]]. Mathematical models that seek to reflect the complexity of the natural setting may assist in planning harvesting strategies and sustaining fishing grounds.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Berezansky|first=L.|last2=Idels|first2=L.|last3=Kipnis|first3=M.|date=2011|title=Mathematical model of marine protected areas|url=http://imamat.oxfordjournals.org/content/76/2/312|journal=IMA Journal of Applied Mathematics|language=en|volume=76|issue=2|pages=312\u2013325|doi=10.1093/imamat/hxq043|hdl=10613/2741|issn=0272-4960|id=Preprint: http://hdl.handle.net/10613/2741|hdl-access=free}}</ref>\n\n== Coral reefs ==\nCoral reef systems have been in decline worldwide. Causes include overfishing, pollution and [[ocean acidification]]. As of 2013 30% of the world's reefs were severely damaged. Approximately 60% will be lost by 2030 without enhanced protection.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Pandolfi|first=J.M.|title=Global trajectories of long-term decline of coral reef ecosystems|journal=Science|volume=301|year=2003|issue=5635|pages=955\u2013958|doi=10.1126/science.1085706 |display-authors=etal|pmid=12920296}}</ref> Marine reserves with \"no take zones\" are the most effective form of protection.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Hughes|first=T.P.|title=Climate change, human impacts, and the resilience of coral reefs|journal=Science|volume=301|year=2003|issue=5635|pages=929\u2013933| doi=10.1126/science.1085046 |display-authors=etal|pmid=12920289}}</ref> Only about 0.01% of the world's coral reefs are inside effective MPAs.<ref name=\"MoraScience2006\">{{cite journal | url=http://www.soc.hawaii.edu/mora/Publications/Mora%20015.pdf | author=Mora C. | year=2006 | title=Coral reefs and the global network of Marine Protected Areas | journal=Science | volume = 312 | issue=5781 | pages = 1750\u20131751 | pmid=16794065 | author2=Andr\u00e8fou\u00ebt, S | author3=Costello, M. J. | author4=Kranenburg, C | author5=Rollo, A | author6=Veron, J | author7=Gaston, K. J. | author8=Myers, R. A. | doi=10.1126/science.1125295 |display-authors=etal}}</ref>\n\n== Fish ==\nMPAs can be an effective tool to maintain fish populations; see [[refuge (ecology)]]. The general concept is to create overpopulation within the MPA. The fish expand into the surrounding areas to reduce crowding, increasing the population of unprotected areas.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://innri.unuftp.is/pdf/Marine%20Protected%20Areas.pdf|title=Marine Protected Areas (Innri)|author=|date=|website=unuftp.is}}</ref> This helps support local fisheries in the surrounding area, while maintaining a healthy population within the MPA. Such MPAs are most commonly used for coral reef ecosystems.\n\nOne example is at Goat Island Bay in New Zealand, established in 1977. Research gathered at Goat Bay documented the spillover effect. \"Spillover and larval export\u2014the drifting of millions of eggs and larvae beyond the reserve\u2014have become central concepts of marine conservation\". This positively impacted commercial fishermen in surrounding areas.<ref>Warne, Kennedy. [http://ngm.nationalgeographic.com/2007/04/table-of-contents] \"Saving the Sea's Bounty\"] National Geographic. April 2007.</ref>\n\nAnother unexpected result of MPAs is their impact on predatory marine species, which in some conditions can increase in population. When this occurs, prey populations decrease. One study showed that in 21 out of 39 cases, \"trophic cascades,\" caused a decrease in herbivores, which led to an increase in the quantity of plant life. (This occurred in the Malindi Kisite and Watamu Marian National Parks in Kenya; the Leigh Marine Reserve in New Zealand; and Brackett's Landing Conservation Area in the US.<ref>MPA News, [https://mpanews.openchannels.org/mpanews/issue/july-2004-61 Vol. 6 No. 1, July 2004]</ref>\n\n== Success criteria ==\nBoth [[Convention on Biological Diversity|CBD]] and [[IUCN]] have criteria for setting up and maintaining MPA networks, which emphasize 4 factors:<ref name=\"Wells17\">{{harvnb|Wells|Sheppard|van_Lavieren|Barnard|2008|p=17}}\nThe [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]] defines a ''protected area'' as:\n<blockquote>\"A clearly defined geographical space, recognized, dedicated, and managed, through legal or effective means, to achieve the long-term conservation of nature with associated ecosystem service and cultural value.\"</blockquote></ref>\n*'''Adequacy'''\u2014ensuring that the sites have the size, shape, and distribution to ensure the success of selected species.\n*'''Representability'''\u2014protection for all of the local environment's biological processes\n*'''Resilience'''\u2014the resistance of the system to natural disaster, such as a tsunami or flood.\n*'''Connectivity'''\u2014maintaining population links across nearby MPAs.\n\n== Misconceptions ==\nMisconceptions about MPAs include the belief that all MPAs are no-take or no-fishing areas. However, less than 1 percent of US waters are no-take areas. MPA activities can include consumption fishing, diving and other activities.\n\nAnother misconception is that most MPAs are federally managed. Instead, MPAs are managed under hundreds of laws and jurisdictions. They can exist in state, commonwealth, territory and tribal waters.\n\nAnother misconception is that a federal mandate dedicates a set percentage of ocean to MPAs. Instead the mandate requires an evaluation of current MPAs and creates a public resource on current MPAs.<ref>[http://mpa.gov/pdf/helpful-resources/factsheets/mpamisconceptions2.pdf]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130215150109/http://mpa.gov/pdf/helpful-resources/factsheets/mpamisconceptions2.pdf |date=February 15, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n== Criticism ==\nSome existing and proposed MPAs have been criticized by indigenous populations and their supporters, as impinging on land usage rights. For example, the proposed Chagos Protected Area in the Chagos Islands is contested by [[Chagossians]] deported from their homeland in 1965 by the [[United Kingdom|British]] as part of the creation of the [[British Indian Ocean Territory]] (BIOT). According to [[WikiLeaks]] [[CableGate]] documents,<ref name=\"[http://www.indybay.org/newsitems/2010/12/23/18667425.php]\">{{cite web |url=http://www.indybay.org/newsitems/2010/12/23/18667425.php |title=WikiLeaks reveals U.S., British use marine reserves as tool of imperialism |accessdate=2010-12-24 |date=2009-05-15 |work=Embassy London}}</ref> the UK proposed that the BIOT become a \"marine reserve\" with the aim of preventing the former inhabitants from returning to their lands and to protect the joint UK/US military base on [[Diego Garcia]] Island.\n\nOther critiques include: their cost (higher than that of passive management), conflicts with human development goals, inadequate scope to address factors such as climate change and invasive species.<ref name=\"MoraAndSale2011\" />\n\nIn Scotland, environmental groups have criticised the government for failing to enforce fishing rules around MPAs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theferret.scot/fines-fishermen-prosecution/|title=Fines to rogue fishermen fall and illegal fishing escapes prosecution|date=2019-10-06|website=The Ferret|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-10-06}}</ref>\n\n== Recent research ==\n[[File:Zebrasoma flavescens Luc Viatour.jpg|thumb|right|The larvae of the [[yellow tang]] can drift more than 100 miles and reseed in a distant location.<ref name=Christie2010 />]]\n\nIn 2010, one study found that [[fish larvae]] can drift on ocean currents and reseed [[fish stock]]s at a distant location. This finding demonstrated that fish populations can be connected to distant locations through the process of larval drift.<ref name=Christie2010>Christie MR, Tissot BN, Albins MA, Beets3 JP, Jia Y, Ortiz DL, Thompson SE, Hixon MA (2010) [http://www.plosone.org/article/info%3Adoi%2F10.1371%2Fjournal.pone.0015715 Larval Connectivity in an Effective Network of Marine Protected Areas] ''PLoS ONE'', '''5'''(12) {{doi|10.1371/journal.pone.0015715}}</ref>\n\nThey investigated the [[yellow tang]], because larva of this species stay in the general area of the reef in which they first settle.<ref name=ScienceDaily /> The tropical yellow tang is heavily fished by the [[aquarium]] trade. By the late 1990s, their stocks were collapsing. Nine MPAs were established off the coast of Hawaii to protect them. Larval drift has helped them establish themselves in different locations, and the fishery is recovering.<ref name=ScienceDaily /> \"We've clearly shown that fish larvae that were spawned inside marine reserves can drift with currents and replenish fished areas long distances away,\" said coauthor Mark Hixon.<ref name=ScienceDaily>[https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2010/12/101222173105.htm Drifting Fish Larvae Allow Marine Reserves to Rebuild Fisheries] ''ScienceDaily '', 26 December 2010.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Marine spatial planning]]\n*[[Special Protection Area]]\n*[[Specially Protected Areas of Mediterranean Importance]]\n*[[United States National Marine Sanctuary]]\n*[[Law of the sea]]\n*[[Marine park]]\n*[[Important marine mammal area]]\n\n== References ==\n=== Citations ===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n=== Sources ===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite web\n|url = https://archive.org/details/nationalregional08well\n|title = National and Regional Networks of Marine Protected Areas:A Review of Progress |last1=Wells |first1=Sue|last2=Sheppard |first2=V. |last3=van Lavieren |first3=H. |last4=Barnard |first4=N. |last5=Kershaw |first5=F. |last6=Corrigan |first6=C. |last7=Teleki |first7=K. |last8=Stock |first8=P. |last9=Adler |first9=E. |year=2008\n|work=Master Evaluation for the UN Effort |publisher=[[World Conservation Monitoring Centre]] The Americas |accessdate=2009-03-18 |ref = harv }}\n* {{cite journal |first1=D. |last1=Smith |first2=K.A. |last2=Miller |title=Safe Harbors for our Future: An Overview of Marine Protected Areas |editor-first = S.F. |editor-last = Norton |journal = Diving for Science |volume = Proceedings of the American Academy of Underwater Sciences |issue = 22nd Annual Scientific Diving Symposium |year = 2003 |url = http://archive.rubicon-foundation.org/4759 |accessdate=2008-08-13 |ref = harv }}\n* {{cite book |last = Australian Government |first = Department of the Environment and Water Resources |author-link = Department of the Environment, Water, Heritage and the Arts (Australia) |title = Growing up strong: The first 10 years of Indigenous Protected Areas in Australia |location = Canberra |publisher = Australian Government\n|date = May 2007\n|url = http://www.environment.gov.au/indigenous/publications/pubs/ipa-growing-up-strong.pdf\n|acce